{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958031401/0198.xml":{"full_text":"United Labor\nCommittee News\nM\nc\nmum\nGoldwater, Mundt, Curtis Use\nKohler Probe to Smear UAW\nAn investigation of the 45-month old strike by the\nUAW at the Kohler Co., Sheboygan, Wis., headed into its\nfourth week with three Republican members of the Me-.\nClellan Special Senate committee making a partisan effort\n1\nto brand the UAW as \u201cviolent.\u201d\nThe three\u2014Senators Barry\nGoldwater (Ariz. Carl T.\nCurtis (Neb.), and Karl\nMundt (S.D )\u2014substantially\ntook over the examination of,\nwitnesses in an effort to show\nthat non-strikers suffered from\nmass picketing, paint throwing,\n\u201cdemonstrations\u201d at their homes\nby strikers, and frequent and\nabusive telephone calls\nUnion witnesses told of acts)\nof intimidation, property damage'\nand harassment during the strike\nwhich a NLRB examiner said\narose from the company's un\nfair labor practices and refusal\nto bargain collectively in good\nfaith\nReuther Challenges Goldwater\nMeanwhile, UAW President\nWalter P. Reuther proposed that\nSenator Goldwater and his Re\npublican colleagues on the com\nmittee \u201cdiscuss the Kohler sit\nuation on its merits and on the\nbasis of the facts\nHe described his proposal in\na letter as an \u201cappeal for sani\nty and responsibility.\u201d\nIn the same letter, and as an\naction separate and apart from\nthe current hearing, Mr Reu\nther offered to resign as UAW\npresident, as an AFL-CIO vice\npresident and from the labor\nmovement entirely, if Senator\nGoldwater could substantiate his\ncharge that \u201cWalter Reuther and\nthe UAW are a more dangerous\nmenace than the sputniks or any\nthing Russia might do.\u201d\nMr Reuther proposed that the\ncharges be heard by a panel of\nnationally prominent clergymen\nselected by Senator Goldwater\nand himself.\n\u201cIf they decide you have not\nsubstantiated your charge,\u201d he\nwrote, \u201cI would leave it up to\nyour own conscience as to\nwhether you would consider\nyourself fit to continue to play\na role in American public life\n1\nMr. Reuther\u2019s offer was\nre\njected by Senator Goldwater\nwho claimed it was a \u201cpublicity\ngimmick.\"\nKohler Blamed For Strike\nin another development at the\nhearing, Emil Mazey. UAW sec\nretary-treasurer, placed full re\nsponsibility for the Kohler Co\nstrike on the firm's\nmanage\nment which, he said, was \"cold\nly brutal and callous, contempt\nuous of the rights and needs of\nits employees, and determined\nto destroy the union\nMr Mazey offered to let mem\nbers of the McClellan Committee\narbitrate the dispute and pro\nmised that the UAW would\nabide by its decision\nThe offer was rejected by Ly\nman Conger, attorney for the\ncompany\nIn a statement to the commit\nfee, Mazey said the Kohler Co\nwas found guilty of violating the\nNational Labor Relations Act\nby a trial examiner He charged\nthat the company had deliberate\nly operated \u201coutside the bounds\nof human decency in its relations\nwith its workers, their families\nand the citizens of the Sheboy\ngan community.\u201d\nUnion Gave Ground\nIn an analysia of the collective\nbargaining sessions held be\ntween Local 833 and the com\npany in 1934 and later, Mazey\nshowed the union had \u201cwith\nun\nderstandable reluctance\u201d stead\nily given ground on every\njor issue, while the Kohler i\nma\nman\nagement had remained \u201ctotallyj\nrigid from the beginning 1\nMazey quoted the trail exam-1\niner of the NLRB, who following\nmore than two years of hearings\nduring which 20,000 pages of\ntestimony were taken, found the\ncompany guilty of violating the\nlaw and who remarked in his\ndecision that the company was\nbargaining \u201cnot to reach but to\navoid agreement.\u201d\nHe emphasized a number of\n\u201cinhuman, unsafe and hazardous\nworking conditions\" which were\nthe source of most of the dis\nsatisfaction of Kohler workers.\nAmong those listed were the\nfollowing:\nWorkers in the enamel\nware department\nwere\nre\nquired to work eight straight\nhours, in temperatures rang\ning from 100 to 250 degrees\nfahrenheit, without either rest\nor lunch periods\nDespite a high incidence\nof silicosis, known in the area\nas \u201cKohler disease\" in the\nplant, the company had re\nfused to make improvement to\nminimize the serious health\nhazard and had persistently\nrefused to make available to a\nworker\u2019s private physician,\nthe results of company medi\ncal examinations.\nThe company opposed\nleaves for female workers and\nat collective bargaining ses\nsions, adopted an indifferent\nand obscene attitude toward\nthe matter.\nReferring tn the company\u2019s\nwidespread charges that the un\nion had engaged in lawless ac\ntivities, Mazey pointed out that\nthat it was the company, not the\nunion, which had consistently\nrelied \u201con force of arms,\" had,\naccording to the NLRB examiner\nreactivated\n'certain equipment\nwhich had been used during the\nviolent strike of 1934;\" had\nstored an arsenal of weapons\nand tear gas inside the plant in\npreparation for the strike, and\nhad recruited and trained a pri\nvate army of special policement\nto break the strike, if possible.\nCompany Hoaxes Exposed\nin addition, Mazey exposed a\nnumber of company-inspired\nhoaxes designed to discredit the\nUnion and its membership.\nMcClellan Scores\nKohler \u2018Maneuver\u2019\nAn apparent Kohler Co. ef\nfort to obtain pictures sug\ngesting that non-Republicans\nwhitewash\u201d\nthe\nwanted to\nUAW blew up when a com\npany publicity man reluctant\nly acknowledged he had or\ndered pictures of any senator\nor committee staff member\nconversing with UAW at\ntorney Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.\nLyman P. Conger, company\nlayer, testified that the firm\nhad no \u201csinister\u201d objective in\nwanting pictures, but pub\nlicity agent George C. Gallati\nfinally conceded that he had\nengaged the United Press\ncommercial photography di\nvision for the \u201csole purpose\u201d\nof getting pictures of commit\ntee and staff members in dis\ncussions with Rauh.\nCommittee Chairman John\nL. McClellan (D., Ark.) angri\nly denounced the maneuver\nas \u201cpretty low\u2014pretty rot\nten,\u201d and charged that the\ncompany wanted to \u201csmear.\u201d\nGallati suddenly said under\noath that he had lost Interest\nin the pictures he had order\ned.\nGallati claimed he wanted\nthe pictures merely for the\ncompany\u2019s\n\u201chouse o r g a n.\u201d\nThe UP said it had agreed to\nfurnish photographs only on\nassurance that they were not\nfor \u201cpublication of any kind.\u201d\n\u201cThe company,\u201d he said,\n\u201cwhile making speeches all over\nthe country denouncing the Un\nion for lawlessness, deliberately\nand calculatedly set out on a\ncourse of action which attempted\nto provoke violence and encour\nage vandalism.\n\u201cWhen this apparently did not\nprove enough, the company en\ngaged in the highly dubious busi\nness of manufacturing incidents\nto alleged violence.\n\"The men and women of Local\n833 have clearly indicated their\ndetermination to win justice\nfrom this arrogant and despotic\ncompany,\u201d Mazey said.\n\u201cThat determination is as firm\ntoday as it was in April of 1954\nwhen the strike began. I can as\nsure you it will not diminish.\u201d\n\"Now, let\u2019s turn on 'EYE OPENER\u2019!\u201d\nLISTEN to EYE OPENER with GUY NUNN\nFeaturing MUSIC NEWS WEATHER SPORTS\nMon. thru Frt., 6:15 a.m., CKLW, 800 on your dial\npresented public service by the UAW\nSpicer Workers Sign\nUp for ULC\nMore than 300 members' of the Spicer\nUnit of Local 12 UAW signed United La\nbor Committee membership cards in a\nwhirlwind one-day drive in the plant last\nFriday. Departmental stewards, armed\nwith cards and information, contacted\nevery worker during the day to explain\nthe work of the ULC in the political field.\nHere, Steward Sigmond Chopcinski, left,\nsigns up three workers in his depart\nment, Lewis Staup, Clyde Spence and\nWayne Swehla.\n\u2014Union Journal Photo\nMeany Calls Jobless\nNo. 1 Concern in U.S.\nIt\u2019s time for the country to take a good look at the\neconomy and do something about it on the basis of action\u2014\nnot words, AFL-CIO Pres. George Meany told the fourth\nlegislative conference of the AFL-CIO Building Construc\ntion Trades Dept, in Washington.\nMeany cited unemploy\nment, \u201capproaching the 5\nmillion mark,\" as \u201cthe No. 1\nconcern\nsaid that\nof all Americans, and\ndespite forecasts of\nAdministration\nEisenhower\nspokesmen of an upturn in\nfew weeks or a few months,\n\u201chave to look at the\n'a\nworkers\nsituation from a practical point\nof view.\u201d\nHe outlined a program of gov\nernment action aimed at stimu\nlating employment and putting\npurchasing power \u201cin the hands\nworking people who spend\nof\nthe market\ntheir earnings in\nand not disbursing\nplace s.\u201d\nmoney \"as\ndividends for high\npaid executives.\"\nMeany specifically called for\nschool, road\nfederal housing,\nand hospital construction pro\ngrams as sources of new Jobs\nwhich particularly would benefit\nbuilding trades workers. i\n\u201cThis industry is a good place,\nto start,\u201d he said. \u201cThis is a\ngood industry to lead the way:\n_1 12. 11*\nand get this country behind us\non the road out of this reces-i\nsion.\u201d\nHe said the government has\nto go into housing, where we\nalso have the incentive of seeing\nthat people have decent places\nto live in.\" He called a federal\nhousing program a necessity.\nMeany also called for a boost\nin the minimum wage to $1.25\nan hour, a program of govern\nment loans to small business, a\ntax cut for low income taxpay\ners, and increased unemploy\nment compensation\nHas Started to Worry\nHe said he \u201cnever really wor\nried\u201d about the economic situa\ntion until recently.\n\u201cThen I read a speech by for\nPres Herbert Hoover say\nmer\nH IC1 4 4 V V T\ning things were going to be an\nright,\u201d he explained \u201cThat\u2019s\nwhen I really started to worry\nHe pledged complete support\nof AFL-CIO officers and the\nDept, of Legislation in helping\nthe building trades department\nand its president, Richard J.\nGray, who presided at the con\nference, \u201csee if we can't give the\nof this country a shot\neconomy\nin the arm.\u201d\nAFL-CIO Legislative Director\nAndrew J. Biemiller, advocating\nthe same program of federal ac\ntion Meany urged, was sharply\ncritical of the Eisenhower Ad\nministration for permitting un\nemployment to soar and not do\ning anything about it.\n\"Let us not forget the great\nparadox of this recession,\" he\nsaid. f Although purchasing pow\ner is declining, prices continue\nto go up and up. So those who\ner\nGRANDMA\nCH, BOY THIS\nFRESH,CLEAN\nWOW GIVES\n\nME AN IDEA\nIT\u2019LL BE A GOOD JOKE ON\nTH1 KIDS IF I CAN OO\nNOW r HOLD MY OTHER\nFOOT UP OFF THE SNOW-\u201d)\n_ By Charles Kuhn\nH-M--LET\u2018S SEE TH' KIDS W/\nFIGURI THAT OUT.\u2019mo7\nJITTER\ni\nWulY PAY OUT GOOD MONEY\nWHEN WE WAVE JITTER\n2\u2018er\u2018\nKr\nL\nOu,OH,..HE\u2018S stuck Too!\nBy ARTHUR POINTER\nSuucks,nus WONT cosr MIKU.\nNOT OVER A COUPLE (e2\nWUNOREo Bucks/ J .33\nF\n1\nsuffer drastically curtailed in\ncomes due to unemployment or\nreduced pay checks furthermore\nfind that their dollars buy less\nthan ever.\u201d\nNLRB Overturns\nPro-Labor Report\nA trial examiner\u2019s report\naccusing the Howard Aero\nCo. of unfair labor practices\nagainst members of the\nAuto Workers at its San\nAntonio, Tex., plant, has\nbeen reversed by the Na\ntional Labor Relations\nBoard.\nA three-man panel in\nstead found the workers at\nfault, and dismissed the\ncomplaint against the com\npany. The panel consisted of\nPhilip Ray Rodgers, Step\nhen S. ean and Joseph A.\nJenkins.\nThe trial examiner, Ar\nthur E. Reyman, found that\nthe company in fighting a\nUAW organizing drive dis\ncriminated against certain\nemployes because they were\nmembers of the union, that\nits Interrogations and sur\nveillance of employes in\nterfered with their rights\no f self-organization and\nthat the firing of men for\nfailure to observe \"no\nsmoking\u201d rules actually\ntook place to discourage un\nion activities.\nGroups Act To Save\nInspection Of Meat\nEight national consumer,\nfarm, public health, business and\nlabor organizations have appeal\ned to Pres. Eisenhower and Con\ngress \"to save the meat inspec\ntion program.\u201d\nThe Amalgamated Meat Cut\nters and Butcher Workmen join\ned in the statement which noted\na $1,392,000 slash in budget re\nquests for fiscal 1959.\nJ. F. ANDERSON\nCOMPANY, INC.\nResidential and Commercial\nConstruction\nCOMPLETE REMODELING AND\nMODERNIZATION SERVICE\n2852\nSouth\nWA 3414\nA. J. Lee Insurance\nAll Kinds of Insurance\nSpitzer Bldg. CH. 1-9517\nCommittee\nVotes U.S.\nPay Boost\nWage increases amounting to\nnearly $1 billion for about 1.5\nmillion federal government em\nploye:\npostal, white collar,\nlegislative and judicial\u2014have\nbeen approved by the House Post\nOffice and Civil Service Com\nmittee.\nThe Senate, meantime, com\npleted action on another bill\nboosting postal rates and as this\nedition of The AFL-CIO News\nwent to press was preparing to\ntake up a proviso tieing to it\npay boosts totaling $317 million\nfor some 500,000 postal workers.\nRetroactive To Last August\nThe House bill would give the\npostal employes an average 15\npercent pay increase, with an 11\npercent average hike for other\nwhite collar government work\ners. Both increases would be re\ntroactive to Aug. 25, 1957. They\nwon an overwhelming 18 to 3\nvote in the committee, with most\nof the Republicans as well as\nDemocrats supporting it.\nThe proposed Senate pay\nboost for postal workers, ap\nproved by the Committee on\nPost Office and Civil Service,\nprovides for an average 12.5\npercent increase. The commit\ntee also approved an average\n7.5 percent raise for other\nfederal white collar employes.\nThe House bill would increase\nthe present $2,880 a year mini\nmum to $3,405, and the top\nsalary from the present $16,000\nto $17,600. The increases would\nrange from 18 percent in the\nlowest pay level to 10 percent\nin the highest. The 350,000\nclerks and carriers would get\nfrom 15 to 16.5 percent.\nPres. Eisenhower has recom\nmended a general increase of 6\npercent for postal employes and\nincreases from 6 to 7.5 percent\nfor most other government white\ncollar workers, effective in both\ncases next July 1.\nThe Senate's postal rate in\ncrease bill would boost the\npresent first class letter mail\nfee of 3 cents to 4 cents for\nlocal deliveries and 5 cents\nfor out of town letters.\nIncreases also were provided\nfor mail falling into other\nclasses.\nLeaders in both branches were\nconcerned lest the pay hike pro\nposals be so high that Eisenhow\ner will veto them. Last year, he\npocket vetoed wage increases\nfor both postal and classified\nfederal employes.\nHOLMES\nWindow Cleaning Service\nk FREE ESTIMATES\n1118 W. Bancroft CH. 6-7965\n1\n0\nan\nTHE COST OF LIVING hit an all-time high in Jan\nuary, the same month in which more workers were unem\nployed than at any time in the past eight years.\nPrices for goods and services have now risen almost\nwithout a letup during the past 23 months.\nAnd Commissioner Ewan\nClague of the Bureau of La\nbor Statistics, who makes the\nmonthly report on living costs,\nsaid that he doubted prices\nwould drop in February or\nMarch.\nIn January, the average city\nfamily had to pay 31 per cent\nmore for goods and services than\nit did a year earlier. They also\npaid $12.23 for the same goods\nand services which cost $10 in\n1947-40\u2014or a jump of 22.3 per\ncent.\nThe increase in prices and the\ndecrease in hours worked cut\nthe purchasing power of fac\ntory workers\u2019 take-home pay by\nabout 2 per cent from that of\nDecember. The drop was more\nthan 43 per cent contrasted to\nJanuary 1057.\nNever before has a con\ntinued rise in unemployment\ntaken place at the same time\nthat there has been a con\ntinued rise in the cost of liv\ning.\nHOW RECESSION GOT\nPUSH DOWNHILL: \u201cThe evi\ndence now strongly points to\nthe conclusion that both the Ad\nministration and the Federal\nReserve authorities believe that\na \u2018moderate recession now\u2019\nwould be a small price to pay\nfor the avoidance of another\nboom and bust later on.\u201d\u2014New\nYork Journal of Commerce,\nJuly 1957.\nagain and again, in off\nthe-record conversations in\nWashington this is what, in ef\nfect, I have heard: \u2018A little\ntemporary suffering among a\nfew millions of us now is far\npreferable to the risk of pro\nlonged suffering among all of\nus later .\u2019.\u201d\u2014Sylvia Porter,\nfinancial columnist in the New\nYork Post, Aug. 1, 1957.\nJOBLESS INSURANCE PAY\nMENTS at peak: More workers\nwere drawing unemployment in\nsurance payments during the\nweek ending February 15\u2014the\nlatest date for which figures\nare available\u2014than at any time\nsince the jobless compensation\nsystem began paying benefits in\n1939.\nThe number, 3,130,200, rep\nresents those persons claiming\nbenefits after being out of work\none week or more.\nADMINISTRATION PLAN\nNED RECESSION: The present\nrecession was manufactured by\nthe government and manage\nment to bring labor leaders into\nline, according to the financial\ncolumnist of the New York\nWorld Telegram and Sun. Ad\ndressing members of a St.\nPetersburg, Fla., securities firm,\nWalter Gutman said:\n\u201cOur present recession or de\npression was manufactured.\nThey got it because they wanted\nit. The government was making\nefforts to tone down Wall\nOne\nreason\nwas\nthat\nStreet.\nthey wanted to prevent infla-\u2019.\ntion. Then they wanted a situa\ntion where management could\ncombat labor.\u201d\nSpeaking to a meeting of\nCommunications Workers in\nChicago, Sen Hubert Humphrey\n(D., Minn.) said: \u201cThe fingers\nof the (Eisenhower) Adminis\ntration are all over this reces\nsion.\u201d Humphrey charged that\nthe slump is a \"planned, pre\nmeditated recession on the part\nof the key financial figures from\nthe business community who\nare dictating the Administra\ntion\u2019s economic policy.\u201d\nLESSON WELL LEARNED:\nThe Washington R e p u blican\nState Central Committee has\ntaken a stand against the so\ncalled \u201cright-to-work\u201d law.\u201d\nMeeting in Yakima on Feb. 1,\nthe committee voted 94 to 24\n'in a secret ballot in opposition\nto Initiative 202. a right-to-scab\nmeasure. The Democratic Party\nalso is opposed to the wreck-the\nunion proposal.\nIn 1956, the Washington State\nGOP dodged a definite stand on\nan initiative intended to kill\nunions. In the elections of that\nyear, the Republicans failed to\n'carry a single state partisan ad\nministrative office.\nI\nI\nCROSSWORD\nLAST WEEK'S\nANSWER\nACROSS\n1. Begone!\n5. Prostrate\nS.A fine\nchina\n10. Dipped,\nas\nwater\n12. Lodge\ndoor\nkeeper\n13. Strange*\n14. Burden\n15. Youth\n16. Tantalum\n(sym.)\nIT. Mayan\nIndian\n(Mex.)\n18. River\n(Swits.)\n19. Church\nbench\nSO. Capital\n(N.Y.)\n33. Noble\nman\n23. European\ntongue\n15. Rattan\n(bot.)\nST. Mistakes\n30. An\noutcry\n81. Asian\nox\n32. Tear\nS3. Erbium\n(sym.)\n34. Medieval\nboat\n35. Storm\n30. Spur\nwheel\n38. A disciple\n3\u00bb. Test\n40. Aside\n41. Pismires\n(SBoteh\nDOWN\n1.\nanesthesia\n2. Dovelike\n3. Fruit\ndrinks\n4 Thrice\n(mua)\n3 Bridge\nplatform\n6 Gentle\nwoman\nT. Affix\n8. Seesaw\n5. Mouth\nMke\nopening\n(bioL).\n11. Speak\nslowly\n15. sauce\nflavor,\ning\n10 Literary\nscraps\nIS. Unob\nstructed\nviews\n31. De\nvoured\n33. Audi,\nence\n14. Vex\n25. Flint\nlike\nrock\n30. Day\nbreak\n30. Diffi\nculties\naBua 00B\nHUIL GluS\n\"REE BU0E\ndue J. 90\n0EH0@s SID I\n000 03E\nOEG0 avu@g\n(3 dOJa\nD3 SOIIUC\nHG uua 203E\n3(4 29030\nBUEOC Hula\n\nHBOP BEES\nP-273\n30. Ex\nhausted\nSI. Shrieks\n34. Tidy\n35. Mature\n37. Gain\n38. Golfer\nSnead\n\n(R\nC\nVIRGIL\nWEI Ta 1\nBULD A SNOWMAN\n@ONBONE\nWRECKS\n80\nCM\nFOR\nMEANGI\nSAKS\nI\n-BUUDONE\nOUTSDE OF MM\nWIJDOW AND ILL\nSee THAT NOTHINS\nHAPPENS TO IT\n1\nf\nBy Len Kleis\nc\nNUTT AND JEFF\nn sick AND TIRED OF\nROOMING WITH MUTT! ILL\n60 NUTS IF I HAUS TO\nSPEND ANOTHER DAV\nIN THE SAME HOUSE?\n27779\nh\"t\nX\nM\n\u2018MuTT,rVE HAO IT! V\nI CAN\u2019T STAND ANOTHER\nMINUTE OF LOOKING\nAT YOU! IM GONNA\nGET A ROOM OF /\u2014g\nr MV OWN P 2\n\n\u201cYe\nw\nt\nBY AL SMITH\nV\n4","height":"26884","width":"19512"}}
